drain from puncta directly into the nasal cavity","Tears flow from canaliculi to puncta to nasolacrimal duct"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct flow of tears is: lacrimal gland \u2192 \u003Cstrong\u003Elacrimal gland ducts empty into the superior fornix of the conjunctiva\u003C/strong\u003E \u2192 tears spread across eye surface \u2192 drain through puncta \u2192 canaliculi \u2192 nasolacrimal sac \u2192 nasolacrimal duct \u2192 inferior meatus of nasal cavity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELacrimal gland ducts empty into the inferior meatus\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the lacrimal gland ducts empty into the superior fornix of the conjunctiva, not the inferior meatus. \u003Cstrong\u003ENasolacrimal duct empties into the conjunctival sac\u003C/strong\u003E reverses the drainage pathway as the nasolacrimal duct empties into the inferior meatus of the nasal cavity. \u003Cstrong\u003ETears drain from puncta directly into the nasal cavity\u003C/strong\u003E omits the intermediate structures as tears must first pass through the canaliculi and nasolacrimal duct. \u003Cstrong\u003ETears flow from canaliculi to puncta to nasolacrimal duct\u003C/strong\u003E presents the drainage sequence in reverse order, as the correct sequence is puncta to canaliculi to nasolacrimal duct.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The lacrimal gland secretes tears onto the surface of the eye via ducts that empty into the superior fornix of the conjunctiva.","Tears drain from the eye via puncta into canaliculi, then through the nasolacrimal duct which empties into the inferior meatus of the nasal cavity."],"references":["Conrady CD, Joos ZP, Patel BC. Review: The Lacrimal Gland and Its Role in Dry Eye. J Ophthalmol. 2016;2016:7542929. doi: 10.1155/2016/7542929. Epub 2016 Mar 2. PMID: 27042343; PMCID: PMC4793137.","Shumway CL, Motlagh M, Wade M. Anatomy, Head and Neck, Eye Extraocular Muscles. [Updated 2022 Oct 13]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519565/","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u0027s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97905"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16285"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97905"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-26T10:38:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-26T10:40:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8976"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115909"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group